SIMPLE: illustrious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Illustrious
<hw>Il*lus"tri*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>illustris</ets>, prob. for <ets>illuxtris</ets>; fr. <ets>il-</ets>
in + the root of <ets>lucidus</ets> bright: cf. F. <ets>illustre</ets>.
See <er>Lucid</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Possessing luster or
brightness; brilliant; luminous; splendid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Quench the light; thine eyes are guides
<qex>illustrious</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Characterized by greatness, nobleness, etc.;
eminent; conspicuous; distinguished.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Illustrious</qex> earls, renowened everywhere.</q>
<rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Conferring luster or honor; renowned; <as>as,
<ex>illustrious</ex> deeds or titles</as>.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Distinguished; famous; remarkable; brilliant;
conspicuous; noted; celebrated; signal; renowened; eminent; exalted;
noble; glorious. See <er>Distinguished</er>, <er>Famous</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Illustriously</ent>⟦br⟧
